      "name": "t:sections.rich_text.presets.rich_text.name",
      "settings": {
        "width": "full-width",
        "title": "",
        "text": "<h2>LED Light Stick Options for Clean, Flexible Vehicle Lighting</h2><p>If you want a lighting upgrade that’s bright, compact, and easy to place almost anywhere, an <strong>LED Light Stick</strong> is one of the most versatile choices you can make. Light sticks deliver strong output in a slim, low-profile form factor—making them ideal for adding visibility without bulky housings or complicated brackets.</p><p>Whether you’re outfitting a work truck, a service vehicle, or a personal build, a well-chosen <strong>LED Light Stick</strong> can serve as warning lighting, perimeter lighting, scene support, or even a clean accent line—depending on the product type and how you mount it. And if you’re shopping specifically for a <strong>Car Light Stick</strong>, you’ll appreciate how easily these units can integrate into tighter spaces where traditional lights don’t fit.</p><p>This collection page is built to help you choose the right light stick setup quickly—based on real-world use cases and the features that actually matter.</p><h2>What Is an LED Light Stick?</h2><p>An <strong>LED Light Stick</strong> is a slim, linear LED fixture designed to mount to a vehicle’s exterior (or in some cases interior) to provide a wide band of light. Instead of a round or square pod, a light stick gives you a longer light surface—helping you create more even visibility across a grille, bumper, rear door, headache rack, or side panel.</p><p>Depending on the model and intended application, light sticks can be used for:</p><ul><li>Warning and hazard visibility.</li><li>Work-area illumination support.</li><li>Rear and side perimeter lighting.</li><li>Supplementing a primary lighting system.</li><li>Clean, modern-looking accent lines (where applicable).</li></ul><p>The biggest advantage is flexibility: you can place a light stick where it provides the most benefit—without needing a large mounting footprint.</p><h2>Why Light Sticks Are Popular for Trucks, Fleets, and Cars</h2><p>A lot of vehicle lighting solutions are great—until you try to mount them cleanly. Light sticks solve that problem by being slim, adaptable, and easy to position for coverage.</p><p>Top reasons buyers choose an <strong>LED Light Stick</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Low-profile design:</strong> Clean installs that don’t look bulky.</li><li><strong>Wide visibility:</strong> Longer light surface improves presence from multiple angles.</li><li><strong>Versatile mounting:</strong> Works on grilles, bumpers, racks, toolboxes, and rear doors.</li><li><strong>Great for tight spaces:</strong> Ideal when a pod light won’t fit.</li><li><strong>Easy to scale:</strong> Add one, or build a full multi-point setup across the vehicle.</li></ul><p>For a <strong>Car Light Stick</strong> use case, the slim shape is especially helpful—cars often have less room for mounting, and a narrow profile can integrate more discreetly.</p><h2>Common Uses for LED Light Sticks</h2><p>Because light sticks can be installed in so many locations, they show up across a wide range of applications. You’ll commonly see <strong>LED Light Stick</strong> setups on:</p><ul><li>Tow trucks and roadside assistance vehicles.</li><li>Utility and service fleets.</li><li>Construction support vehicles.</li><li>Plow trucks and road maintenance rigs.</li><li>Security and escort vehicles (where permitted).</li><li>Personal trucks and off-road builds.</li><li>Vehicles that need visibility in lots, job sites, or shoulder work.</li></ul><p>Light sticks are often used as part of a layered system—paired with <strong>LED Light Bars</strong>, <strong>Grille Lights</strong>, or <strong>Surface Mount Lights</strong> for complete 360° coverage.</p><h2>Where to Mount a Car Light Stick or Truck Light Stick</h2><p>Placement is everything. The best <strong>Car Light Stick</strong> (or truck setup) is the one aimed where it adds real visibility without being blocked by trim, racks, or accessories.</p><p>Popular mounting locations include:</p><h3>Front: Grille, Lower Bumper, or Push Bumper</h3><p>Front-mounted sticks add a strong forward-facing signal and can be a clean alternative to multiple separate modules.</p><h3>Rear: Tailgate, Rear Door, or Above the Plate Area</h3><p>Rear placement is great for roadside stops, backing awareness, and making your vehicle more visible to approaching traffic.</p><h3>Sides: Rocker Area, Toolboxes, or Rack Rails</h3><p>Side-mounted light sticks improve lateral visibility—especially helpful on job sites or when vehicles are parked in active areas.</p><h3>Racks and Headache Racks</h3><p>High mounting positions can improve line-of-sight and widen the usable coverage area.</p><p>If you’re building a complete visibility package, consider pairing your light sticks with <strong>Warning Lights</strong>, <strong>Work Lights</strong>, or <strong>Scene Lighting,</strong> depending on your job.</p><h2>How to Choose the Right LED Light Stick</h2><p>Not all light sticks are created equal. When shopping this collection, focus on the details that affect performance and longevity—not just looks.</p><h3>1) Purpose: Warning, Work Support, or Accent</h3><p>Start by deciding the primary role:</p><ul><li><strong>Warning visibility:</strong> Prioritize brightness, flash patterns, and wide-angle optics.</li><li><strong>Work support:</strong> Prioritize usable illumination and placement near task areas.</li><li><strong>Accent styling:</strong> Prioritize diffusion and clean integration (where applicable/legal).</li></ul><h3>2) Size and Coverage</h3><p>Longer sticks can provide more presence and more even visibility—but may require more mounting space. Shorter sticks are easier to place and can be combined in multiples for custom layouts.</p><h3>3) Beam/Optics and Viewing Angle</h3><p>A good <strong>LED Light Stick</strong> should be visible from common approach angles—not only straight on. Wider viewing angles are especially useful for intersections, multi-lane roads, and job sites.</p><h3>4) Durability and Weather Resistance</h3><p>Exterior lighting must handle the real world:</p><ul><li>Rain, snow, and road spray.</li><li>Salt, mud, and dust.</li><li>Vibration from rough roads.</li><li>Heat and long run times.</li></ul><h3>5) Wiring and Control Options</h3><p>Think about how you’ll activate your lighting:</p><ul><li>Dedicated switch for the light stick.</li><li>Integration into a larger warning system.</li><li>Separate control for front vs. rear lighting.</li></ul><p>A clean control plan keeps operations simple—especially for fleet drivers who need “one switch and done.”</p><h2>Step-by-Step: Planning an LED Light Stick Install (Before You Buy)</h2><p>This is a practical planning checklist—so you choose the right products and avoid common fitment and placement issues.</p><h3>Step 1: Identify Your Visibility Goals</h3><p>Do you need front warning, rear warning, side visibility, or all three? Start with your most critical zone and build outward.</p><h3>Step 2: Measure Your Mounting Space</h3><p>Measure the area where the light stick will sit (grille opening, tailgate panel, rack rail). Confirm that the stick length fits cleanly and won’t interfere with moving parts.</p><h3>Step 3: Choose a Mounting Location That Won’t Be Blocked</h3><p>Avoid placing the stick behind heavy tint, thick grilles, or accessories that reduce visibility. A clear line-of-sight improves effectiveness.</p><h3>Step 4: Plan Wiring and Switching</h3><p>Decide where the wiring will run and how you’ll control it. Clean routing and protected connections matter for long-term reliability.</p><h3>Step 5: Build a Layered System If Needed</h3><p>If your use case involves roadside work or job-site safety, pair your <strong>LED Light Stick</strong> with <strong>LED Light Bars</strong> or <strong>Surface Mount Lights</strong> for added coverage and redundancy.</p><h2>Light Stick vs. Light Bar vs. Surface Mount: Which Fits Your Build?</h2><p>Each option has its place:</p><ul><li><strong>LED Light Stick:</strong> Slim, flexible placement, clean installs in tight spaces.</li><li><strong>LED light bar:</strong> Maximum visibility and presence, great for fleet standardization.</li><li><strong>Surface mount modules:</strong> Targeted warning in specific areas (grille, rear, sides).</li></ul><p>Many of the best setups combine them—light sticks for clean lines and fill coverage, plus other lights for broad or targeted visibility.</p>",
        "heading_size": "medium",
        "text_alignment": "left"
      }
    },
    "dynamic_rich_text_QkdjdF": {
